{"cursor":"14012","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nIn computing, the 'Advanced Configuration and Power Interface' ('ACPI')\nspecification provides an open standard for device configuration and power\nmanagement by the operating system.\n\nFirst released in December 1996, ACPI defines platform-independent interfaces\nfor hardware discovery, configuration, power management and monitoring. The\nspecification is central to Operating System-directed configuration and Power\nManagement (OSPM), a system implementing ACPI, which removes device management\nresponsibilities from legacy firmware interfaces.\n\nThe standard was originally developed by Intel, Microsoft and Toshiba, and were\nlater joined by HP, and Phoenix. {{cite web\n | url = http://acpi.info/DOWNLOADS/ACPIspec50.pdf format = PDF title = Advanced\n | Configuration and Power Interface Specification, revision 5.0 author = Hewlett-\n | Packard, Intel Corporation, Microsoft, Phoenix Technologies , Toshiba date =\n | 2011-10-23 accessdate = 2011-10-30\n}}  The latest version is \"Revision 5.0\", which was published on\nNovember 23, 2011.\n","linknr":374,"url":"Advanced_Configuration_and_Power_Interface","recorded":1363122544,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Advanced_Configuration_and_Power_Interface&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Advanced_Configuration_and_Power_Interface&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*",